results.notes:
Growing densely gregariously to scattered in a somewhat boggy-grassy/soil area on the edge of a loblolly pine-dominated thicket, with some sweet gum, tulip and young oak present. Found in the exact location and nearly same time of year as Obs 339658.

Micro:
Pileus ~ 3 – 7 cm broad, convex when young, becoming plano-convex to nearly plane in age, sometimes broadly umbonate, dingy-white/cream, appressed-fibrillose, fibrils radially arranged, very dense at disc and breaking up towards margin, fibrils dark brown at disc becoming lighter towards margin, the margin not enrolled (or only slightly at button-stage), with veil remnants intact, generally appendiculate until full maturity, darkening to a very deep brownish color upon drying; Pileus context whitish, smooth, slightly rufescent with context becoming light pinkish when exposed, resolving to a dingy greyish-brown; Lamellae off-white/pallid when young, becoming a greyish-lilac(ish) color and finally dark brown/black, discoloring a pinkish color when damaged/cut; Stipe ~ 5 to 8 cm long and up to a 1 cm wide, lustrous, slightly fibrillose with veil fragments/fibrils near base, mostly equal with tapered base (infrequently bulbous), whitish to off-white becoming copper/light-brownish upon handling, darkening to a dark sordid greyish/brown color within several hours; Stipe context dainty, whitish, with a central cavity, becoming slightly pinkish upon exposure, though generally confined to the upper most portion (with cavity portion essentially unchanging), ultimately darkening similar to stipe surface; Veil whitish with spots of pale browns on the underside (prior to cap expansion), sticking to pileus margin through maturity, appearing to exhibit a banded region closest to stipe (when still intact), upper surface lighter in color, lower surface with brownish tones of which intensify in age, all parts turning golden-brown when handling and in age, sometimes falling off completely in maturity; Odor/Taste odor extremely reminiscent of A. bisporus or the typical ‘grocery store button/white mushroom’, did not taste but presumably similar to that of A. bisporus due to odor;

Chemical/Spot Test: KOH negative on all surfaces/context

Micro:
Basidiospores ellipsoid, brown in water, dark brown in KOH, amber-golden-brown in Melzer’s, thick-walled with a small apiculus, germ pore not observed, ~ 5.0 – 5.8 (6.0 – 6.2) x (3.0 – 3.2) 3.3 – 3.6 (4.0) μm; Q = 1.43 – 1.77 (1.87); N = 18; (95% Conf: L x W = 5.20 – 5.6 × 3.3 – 3.5 μm; Q = 1.54 – 1.66);

Habitat: mixed wood; Fagus sylvatica and Picea abies dominant trees; slightly inclined mountain slope, east aspect; calcareous, colluvial ground; in shade; fairly dry place; partly protected from direct rain by tree canopies; average precipitations ~ 3.000 mm/year, average temperature 7-9 deg C, elevation 555 m (1.820 feet), alpine phytogeographical region.

Substratum: soil.

Place: Lower Trenta valley, between villages Soča and Trenta; right bank of river Soča; near Skokar farmhouse, Trenta 2; East Julian Alps, Posočje, Slovenia EC.

Comments:This find almost certainly belongs to subgenus Russula (Pers.: Fr.) Bon, section Emeticinae, Melzer & Zvara (Ref.: 2). Spore are rather small and correspond to two species listed in Ref.:2: Russula emetica var. sylvestris = Russula silvestris (current name according to Index Fungorum) and Russula emetica var. grisescens. The last one is much bigger than this find and also has grayish stipe. Several other species have been also considered. Russula luteotacta was tentatively proposed (Ref. 1) since habit, habitat and particularly hut colors correspond well to this find (spot wise fading to pinkish and whitish with older specimens). However, gills are not broadly attached or +/- decurrent as they should be with R. luteotacta (Ref.:3). Also similar Russula mairei Sing. was considered. However, measured spores seems to be too broad (5.2-6.6 µm for Russula mairei (Ref.3)). It also has slightly beige spore print and grows on damp soil, which doesn’t fit to this find.

We determined this find to Russula silvestris. This species is found primarily near conifers (particularly Pinus) but also in hardwood and mixed forests including near Fagus and Picea trees (Ref. 3). Nevertheless, the confidence of the determination is not high. Chemical tests and more microscopy would be needed for a more reliable result

Growing solitary and scattered; 10 + pilei on an area of about two m2; pilei diameter 2.9 – 6 cm, hut cuticle peels to about 50% of pilei radius and above; gills bruise slightly yellowish after a longer time (several hours); stipe 2 -4.5 cm long and 0.8 -1.2 cm in diameter; SP abundant, white, oac909.

results.notes:
Two carpophores fruiting adjacent to a very well-decayed, hardwood log solitarily within about a foot of each other.
Macro:
Pileus about 12 – 15 mm wide, ~ 8 mm tall, broadly obtuse, appearing glabrous, striate margin with some very scant, brownish veil remnants adhering to the margin, honey brown to fawn brown in color, darkening in age; Lamellae notched at stipe, blackish brown-vinaceous, edges somewhat crenulate, slightly pallid though splotched with reddish-brown near margin, with a whiteish sheen/pubescence towards stipe; Stipe about 4 – 5 mm long and 2 – 3 mm thick, fragile/dainty, nearly equal with a slightly enlarged base, pruinose at apex, faintly fibrillose below, whitish becoming dingy/sordid when handled or in age; Taste/Odor smell slightly farinaceous to indistinct, did not taste.
Micro:
Basidiospores elliptical to ellipsoid, sometimes slightly curved in profile, apex with distinct germ pore, giving truncated appearance, immature spores very pale brownish/hyaline in KOH, mature spores chocolate brown initially in KOH, becoming a more a darker brown within a few minutes in KOH mount, ~ (8.0 – 9.3) 9.5 – 11.5 (12.0 – 12.2) x (4.4 – 4.5) 4.7 – 5.2 (5.4 – 5.7) μm; Q = 1.8 – 2.4; N = 35; (95% Conf: L x W = 10.1 – 10.8 × 4.8 – 5.1 μm; Q = 2.0 – 2.3); Basidia clavate, 4-spored, brachybasidioles appearing present, though not 100% sure due to the dried material being tough to revive, ~ 19 – 24 × 8 – 10 μm; Pleurocystidia abundant, broadly fusoid with obtuse apex to sublageniform also with obtuse apex, thin walled, intracellular contents present in KOH, hyaline (or nearly so), ~ 25 – 43 × 10 – 17 μm; Q = 2.0 – 3.8; N = 18; (95% Conf: L x W = 31.1 – 36.5 × 11.2 – 12.9 μm; Q = 2.6 – 3.1); Cheilocystidia abundant, subutriform to fusioid-ventricose with broad/obtuse apex, though sometimes narrowly pyriform to clavate, ~ 21 – 36 × 8 – 12.5 μm; Q = 2.1 – 4.4; N = 13; (95% Conf: L x W = 26.5 – 31.2 × 8.4 – 9.9 μm; Q = 2.9 – 3.6); Pileipelis consisting of several rows of globose to oblong cells, thin-walled and collapsing pretty easily, some widely lageniform cells also appearing scattered, though not completely sure if these were some hymenial cystidia that may have gotten mixed in when preparing KOH mount, ~ 20 – 40 × 15 – 35 μm; Clamp Connections not observed, though tissue wasn’t holding up very well, collapsing easily.

- Spore size (N=12, selected for assumed maturity): (8-) 9 – 10 (-10.5) X (5.5-) 6 (-6.5)
